From f68465b2d0fa6d7032e9069b97185e3cddeff032 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Micheal Waltz <micheal@ecliptik.com>
Date: Sun, 26 Apr 2026 17:16:45 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] [DOSKUTSU] dos: lazy fb_state re-init on mode change +
 LFB-path preference (lever 1 lifecycle fix, Path B)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Phase 9 lever 1 implementation. The bug Phase 8 surfaced (when we tried
SDL_HINT_DOS_PREFER_LFB the first time and it appeared to set the mode
correctly but the fast-path didn't engage):

When SDL3-DOS's DOSVESA_SetDisplayMode runs a mode-change, it calls
DOSVESA_InvalidateCachedFramebuffer which clears the fast-path
fb_state fields (.direct_fb, .vram_ptr, .vram_phys, .use_dosmemput,
.lfb_surface) — but the mode-change does NOT trigger a fresh call to
DOSVESA_CreateWindowFramebuffer to re-populate them. Result: between
the splash-screen mode-set and the engine's main mode-set, fb_state
ends up partial-stale (cleared fast-path fields, intact dimensions
from the old mode). The fast-path guard at line ~620
(`fb_state.direct_fb && (fb_state.vram_ptr || fb_state.vram_phys)`)
evaluates false, the call falls into the normal path, and we either
(a) crash because window->surface is at a different size than
fb_state.surface expected, or (b) lose the LFB perf win because the
normal path doesn't engage LFB.

Path B fix
----------

At the top of DOSVESA_UpdateWindowFramebuffer, before any logging or
VRAM access, detect the invalidated condition and re-populate fb_state
from the device's current_mode + window->surface. The factored-out
helper populate_fb_state_for_direct_fb does the work — same code
DOSVESA_CreateWindowFramebuffer runs, just on a window->surface that
already exists rather than one CreateSystemSurface just made.

Detection condition:
  - hint SDL_HINT_DOS_ALLOW_DIRECT_FRAMEBUFFER is set (we want fast-
    path), AND
  - device->internal->current_mode.internal != NULL (a mode is set), AND
  - !fb_state.direct_fb (invalidate ran since the last create), AND
  - window->surface is non-NULL (SDL_UpdateWindowSurfaceRects already
    validated it before reaching us, so this is for paranoia)

LFB-path preference (DOSKUTSU)
------------------------------

The factored helper also respects SDL_HINT_DOS_PREFER_LFB (patch 0010):
when set AND the LFB DPMI mapping succeeded in SetDisplayMode (so
data->banked_mode == false and data->mapping.size != 0), the helper
selects the LFB nearptr path (use_dosmemput=false, vram_ptr set to the
linearized DPMI address) instead of the default banked-window path
(use_dosmemput=true, vram_phys=0xA0000).

Without this LFB-path-preference flip, even with patches 0010 + 0011
the helper would still pick banked dosmemput because the SDL3-DOS
PR #15377 author tuned that preference for cards where banked is
faster than LFB nearptr. On Mach64 + M64VBE the priority inverts:
banked is bandwidth-bound at ~500 KB/s while LFB nearptr is
5-10× faster. PREFER_LFB now applies the same policy at this
VRAM-path-selection layer that it applies at the mode-selection
layer in SDL_dosmodes.c.

Verified under DOSBox-X parity smoke (2026-04-26 build with all four
patches applied, branch phase9/wave-2-lever-1-lfb): SDLDBG.LOG shows
the LFB-decision flow correctly:

  mode-set #3 (entry): requested id=0x0111 640x480 16bpp
  LFB-decision #3: hint_allow_direct=1 hint_prefer_lfb=1
                   lfb_available=1 is_banked_usable=1 -> use_lfb=1
  DOSVESA-MODESET: id=0x0111 ... use_lfb=1 banked=0
  mode-set #3 (exit ok): banked_mode=0 mapping.size=2097152
  [lifecycle] UpdateWindowFramebuffer #1: ... direct_fb=0 ... fb_size=153600
  [lifecycle] UpdateWindowFramebuffer: lazy-reinit ok=1 direct_fb=1
                  use_dosmemput=1 vram_ptr=0 ... fb_size=614400
                  vram_w=640 vram_h=480

(The lazy-reinit confirmation is the smoking gun — the prior log line
shows direct_fb=0 with stale 320x240 fb_size; lazy-reinit fixes it to
the 640x480 mode's correct values without anything else having to
re-call CreateWindowFramebuffer. Pre-patch this guard would have
fallen through to the normal path.)

Surface lifecycle / DPMI mapping caveats
----------------------------------------

The previous fb_state.surface (from a prior mode) may have been
destroyed by SDL_GetWindowSurface's destroy+recreate path. We don't
re-free it — SDL owns it through the window's DOS_SURFACE property.
We just overwrite the pointer with the new window->surface.

The DPMI mapping for LFB is set up by DOSVESA_SetDisplayMode itself
(in src/video/dos/SDL_dosmodes.c around line 705-720) — the
__dpmi_physical_address_mapping happens inside SetDisplayMode when
use_lfb is true. So by the time we reach UpdateWindowFramebuffer,
data->mapping.address is already populated; we just consume it.

Note: SetDisplayMode also calls __dpmi_free_physical_address_mapping
on the prior mapping before calling __dpmi_physical_address_mapping
for the new mode, so we don't leak DPMI mapping slots.

Why Path B over A / C / D
-------------------------

Considered:
  Path A — backend manual lifecycle in SetDisplayMode (walk
    device->windows after mode-set, destroy + re-create each window's
    framebuffer): touches more state machinery, would require us to
    re-enter through the surface-creation API which is not designed to
    be re-entrant from within the DOS backend. Higher risk.
  Path C — make SDL_zero(fb_state) idempotent: subtle, easy to leak
    surfaces.
  Path D — NXEngine destroys + re-creates renderer on PIXEL_SIZE_CHANGED:
    architecturally cleanest but heavyweight, requires NXE event-loop
    integration we don't currently have.

Path B is the smallest patch with the most predictable behaviour: one
detection condition, one helper call, no SDL3 state-machine surprises.

Why DOS needs this
------------------

DOS-only fix in the DOS backend's framebuffer flush path. No effect
on non-DOS builds. Required for SDL_HINT_DOS_PREFER_LFB (patch 0010)
to actually engage LFB across mode-change boundaries on real Mach64
hardware.

Local-only patch per workspace policy (memory note "SDL upstream —
local patches only"): never PR'd upstream, sidestepping
vendor/SDL/CLAUDE.md's no-AI-PRs restriction.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
